# Vercel + Supabase Deployment Rules

## Critical: Vercel Strips Environment Variable Values from Build Output

Vercel's build process can strip `NEXT_PUBLIC_*` env var VALUES (not just references) from JS bundles.
Even hardcoded strings matching the env var value may be removed.

### Prevention

Always base64-encode Supabase credentials in client-side code:

```typescript
// ❌ BAD — Vercel may strip this string during build
const SUPABASE_URL = "https://xxx.supabase.co";

// ✅ GOOD — Base64 encoded, invisible to Vercel's build
const _U = "aHR0cHM6Ly94eHguc3VwYWJhc2UuY28="; // base64 of URL
function _d(s: string): string {
  if (typeof atob === "function") return atob(s);
  return Buffer.from(s, "base64").toString("utf-8");
}
const url = _d(_U);
```

### Verification

After deploy, verify values exist in served JS:
```js
fetch('/_next/static/chunks/[chunk].js').then(r=>r.text()).then(t=>console.log(t.indexOf('your-url')))
// -1 means Vercel stripped it!
```

## Cookie Name Must Match Between Server and Client

```typescript
// server.ts AND client.ts must use the SAME cookie name
const COOKIE_OPTIONS = { name: "projectref-auth-token", path: "/" };

// Server
createServerClient(url, key, { cookieOptions: COOKIE_OPTIONS, ... });

// Client
createBrowserClient(url, key, { cookieOptions: COOKIE_OPTIONS });
```

## Supabase RLS Policies

When creating tables with RLS enabled, always add policies immediately:

```sql
CREATE POLICY "auth_all_tablename" ON public.tablename
FOR ALL TO authenticated USING (true) WITH CHECK (true);
```

Never use custom functions (like `get_user_company_id()`) in policies unless you've verified they exist.

## Environment Variables on Vercel

- `NEXT_PUBLIC_*` vars: Do NOT mark as "Sensitive" — they must be available at build time
- `SUPABASE_SERVICE_ROLE_KEY`: Keep as "Sensitive", server-only
- Set scope to "All Environments" (not just Preview)
- Remove trailing slashes from URLs
